WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:14.200
Hi, so my name is Caroline Ledbetter and I'm going to speak to you about how incorporating

00:00:14.200 --> 00:00:21.200
the Rproject templates can help you standardize and automate your workflow.

00:00:21.200 --> 00:00:24.280
So why Rproject templates?

00:00:24.280 --> 00:00:27.440
If you can automate something, you should automate something.

00:00:27.440 --> 00:00:32.880
Things are that you, when you do Rprojects, you tend to either you as a person or as your

00:00:32.880 --> 00:00:38.520
organization has a standardized file structure, readmes that you like to put into it, maybe

00:00:38.520 --> 00:00:42.759
you always set it up as a GitHub repo, all of these things that are probably unique to

00:00:42.759 --> 00:00:45.639
your workflow or your organization.

00:00:45.639 --> 00:00:51.240
You can set this up to do that automatically for you every time.

00:00:51.240 --> 00:00:56.400
And if you are an organization and you set this up, it ensures that everybody is following

00:00:56.400 --> 00:01:00.799
the same stuff, which helps you in the future.

00:01:00.799 --> 00:01:04.099
So what do you need to set up your own Rproject templates?

00:01:04.099 --> 00:01:05.279
You need an Rproject.

00:01:05.279 --> 00:01:06.720
They have to live in an Rproject.

00:01:06.720 --> 00:01:09.400
This can be just a simple internal project.

00:01:09.400 --> 00:01:10.400
It can live on GitHub.

00:01:10.400 --> 00:01:13.080
It can live wherever your Rprojects live.

00:01:13.080 --> 00:01:18.879
You need a template metadata file and a template function file, and I'm going to show you using

00:01:18.879 --> 00:01:22.559
our internal CetaTools package what those look like.

00:01:22.559 --> 00:01:24.800
So I've highlighted them here.

00:01:24.800 --> 00:01:30.839
So your project setup DCF is your template metadata, and newproject.R is our template

00:01:30.839 --> 00:01:38.000
function, and I'm going to demonstrate how we as an organization use this functionality

00:01:38.000 --> 00:01:39.000
in ours.

00:01:39.000 --> 00:01:40.919
So we have the CetaTools package.

00:01:40.919 --> 00:01:42.680
All of the code is available on GitHub.

00:01:42.680 --> 00:01:50.360
So after this talk, if you want to see exactly all of these steps, you can see it there.

00:01:50.360 --> 00:01:55.339
So for us, we do a lot of scientific research with an academic center.

00:01:55.339 --> 00:01:56.760
So we have principal investigators.

00:01:56.760 --> 00:01:58.320
We have analysts.

00:01:58.320 --> 00:02:02.800
We have a GitLab internal server where we usually store our stuff in Git.

00:02:02.800 --> 00:02:08.240
So you can put all of this information in here, and some of it is optionally stored

00:02:08.240 --> 00:02:15.199
in a DCF file so that it can be referenced in headers and in snippets, and so you don't

00:02:15.199 --> 00:02:19.440
have to keep putting that information for each project in, and it also gives you this

00:02:19.520 --> 00:02:24.839
choice of getting your repo started.

00:02:24.839 --> 00:02:29.479
And so this is just an example of what the template metadata looks like.

00:02:29.479 --> 00:02:35.440
It uses widgets that are very similar to Shiny, if you're familiar with that, but you can

00:02:35.440 --> 00:02:39.720
see right here, you know, from the previous screen, we had the principal investigator

00:02:39.720 --> 00:02:41.399
option.

00:02:41.399 --> 00:02:42.899
It does not have a default.

00:02:42.899 --> 00:02:47.479
You can decide where it goes and in what order and what its label is and stuff like that,

00:02:47.479 --> 00:02:51.320
and what kind of input it is.

00:02:51.320 --> 00:02:56.720
And then this is our project setup function, just to give you an idea of what that looks

00:02:56.720 --> 00:02:57.720
like.

00:02:57.720 --> 00:03:02.199
So all of those parameters that you set up in the previous screen are passed through

00:03:02.199 --> 00:03:08.639
the dots argument, so you access them just like you would access other dots arguments

00:03:08.639 --> 00:03:12.539
through a function.

00:03:12.539 --> 00:03:18.419
And RStudio has a fantastic how-to guide of how to set these up.

00:03:18.419 --> 00:03:20.740
The website is there.

00:03:20.740 --> 00:03:26.300
If you want to check out our repo and see exactly how our stuff is laid out and how

00:03:26.300 --> 00:03:32.059
that might apply to the way you'd like to set up your R project templates, the repo

00:03:32.059 --> 00:03:34.820
is leadbettscetatools.

00:03:34.820 --> 00:03:40.139
And then the slides for this will be up on my website probably tomorrow.

00:03:40.139 --> 00:03:44.500
You can reach me at carolineledbetter at yahoo.com, and you can find me on GitHub and

00:03:44.500 --> 00:03:45.500
Twitter.

00:03:45.500 --> 00:03:46.500
Thank you.

00:03:46.500 --> 00:03:46.500


